00:22:04,240 --> 00:22:06,459
When you're ready, let me know.

237
00:22:06,909 --> 00:22:10,209
Beautiful place, Tucson.
They can breathe out there.

238
00:22:19,296 --> 00:22:21,469
She's sleeping too much.

239
00:22:22,341 --> 00:22:23,934
It's not normal.

240
00:22:24,510 --> 00:22:27,514
I've got a couple of TV dinners
in the oven. Come on.

241
00:22:27,680 --> 00:22:29,307
It'll just be a couple of minutes.

242
00:22:30,808 --> 00:22:32,856
Jack, this drink's enough for me.

243
00:22:33,811 --> 00:22:36,815
- I've never seen you drink without eating.
- I'm not hungry.

244
00:22:37,982 --> 00:22:42,829
I think maybe you ought to
take Carol to see another doctor.

245
00:22:43,487 --> 00:22:47,242
I, uh... I did. Today.
A psychiatrist.

246
00:22:48,284 --> 00:22:52,414
He seems to feel it might help her if I
took her away to another environment.

247
00:22:53,247 --> 00:22:56,592
Out of New York,
on the shore someplace.

248
00:22:56,792 --> 00:22:58,510
Sounds like a good idea.

249
00:22:58,669 --> 00:23:01,923
- I'll go along with you.
- Uh... No, Dad. He...

250
00:23:02,298 --> 00:23:04,524
He seemed to feel that
it might be better if

251
00:23:04,550 --> 00:23:06,874
she didn't have any
association with anyone...

252
00:23:07,011 --> 00:23:10,811
that might remind her of that day.
- How the hell do I remind her of that day?

253
00:23:11,181 --> 00:23:12,979
Well, you know how it is, Dad.

254
00:23:13,309 --> 00:23:15,607
I mean, it happened
in your apartment.

255
00:23:15,978 --> 00:23:20,358
And you're living there.
You remind her of Morn.

256
00:23:22,568 --> 00:23:25,572
Dad, don't make it tough for me.

257
00:23:26,739 --> 00:23:29,583
Okay, I'll make it easy for you.

258
00:23:29,825 --> 00:23:33,500
Ives asked me to go to
Tucson, Arizona on a job.

259
00:23:33,704 --> 00:23:37,800
- How long will you be gone?
- I don't know. Until I look the job over.

260
00:23:38,375 --> 00:23:40,924
But you call me every other day,
let me know how Carol is.

261
00:23:41,420 --> 00:23:43,514
Sure I will, Dad.

262
00:23:44,757 --> 00:23:48,432
You know, that'll be good for you,
I hear Tucson's a really beautiful place.

263
00:23:48,594 --> 00:23:50,437
Yeah, yeah.
That's what everybody says.

264
00:23:58,604 --> 00:24:00,823
How are you today, sir?

265
00:24:45,359 --> 00:24:47,077
Son of a bitch.

266
00:24:47,361 --> 00:24:49,659
Turn around, son of a bitch.

267
00:24:50,030 --> 00:24:52,328
Motherfucker! I said turn around.

268
00:24:52,741 --> 00:24:54,414
And hand me the money.

269
00:26:20,996 --> 00:26:22,373
Paul Kersey.

270
00:26:22,623 --> 00:26:24,967
- Yeah.
- Aimes Jainchill.

271
00:26:25,167 --> 00:26:26,635
How do you do, Mr. Jainchill?

272
00:26:26,794 --> 00:26:29,138
Aimes. I'll call you Paul.
Come on. Let's get your bags.

273
00:26:29,296 --> 00:26:32,266
- How did you know who I was?
- Well, you look like a New Yorker.

274
00:26:40,933 --> 00:26:42,230
Ho!

275
00:26:45,229 --> 00:26:47,527
Ho. Ho, ho.

276
00:26:48,982 --> 00:26:51,201
Howdy, Jud.

277
00:26:58,325 --> 00:27:03,582
I wanted you to see this country before you
looked at the drawings back at the office.

278
00:27:03,956 --> 00:27:05,629
Give you a better idea.

279
00:27:05,999 --> 00:27:07,717
I don't wanna change these hills.

280
00:27:07,876 --> 00:27:10,174
Don't wanna bulldoze them flat.

281
00:27:12,756 --> 00:27:14,929
You'll waste a lot
of building space.

282
00:27:15,717 --> 00:27:18,687
Ha, ha! Wasting space.

283
00:27:18,929 --> 00:27:21,102
Now, those are some words
that you big developers...

284
00:27:21,265 --> 00:27:23,984
have got to change
for something else.

285
00:27:24,143 --> 00:27:25,360
Such as?

286
00:27:25,519 --> 00:27:27,362
Well, space for life.

287
00:27:28,147 --> 00:27:32,527
Like old Jud up there.
Space for people, horses, cows.

288
00:27:33,485 --> 00:27:36,455
I got funny ideas about
building things.

289
00:27:43,912 --> 00:27:47,007
Howdy, folks, welcome to old Tucson,
the famous movie location and studio.

290
00:27:47,207 --> 00:27:48,254
In just a few moments...

291
00:27:48,417 --> 00:27:51,887
Unh. Come on. Let's wet our whistle
before I trot you back to the motel.

292
00:27:52,045 --> 00:27:53,262
Glass of beer, maybe.

293
00:27:53,463 --> 00:27:56,057
Take their positions on the
porches of the Red Dog Cafe...

294
00:27:56,258 --> 00:27:59,057
the Territorial Gunsmith shop...
- What's happening here?

295
00:27:59,219 --> 00:28:01,472
Oh, it's a phony western town.

296
00:28:01,805 --> 00:28:05,730
They shoot movies here sometimes, but the
rest of the time, it's for the tourists.

297
00:28:06,310 --> 00:28:09,405
This is where the actual
performance will take place.

298
00:28:09,605 --> 00:28:11,880
These fellas are pretty good.
Wanna watch?

299
00:28:11,906 --> 00:28:12,474
Sure.

300
00:28:12,649 --> 00:28:14,492
where the Wild West lives again.

301
00:28:15,861 --> 00:28:17,955
- Where's the marshal?
- He's in the bank.

302
00:28:18,155 --> 00:28:20,078
I spotted him through the window
as I came by.

303
00:28:20,240 --> 00:28:23,710
- What have you got in mind to do, then?
- Well, why don't you steal my horse?

304
00:28:23,869 --> 00:28:25,871
All right.
That's a good trick. We'll use it.

305
00:28:26,038 --> 00:28:29,668
You spot yourself on the porch while I
draw the marshal out into the open.

306
00:28:30,083 --> 00:28:31,835
Marshal! Hey, marshal!

307
00:28:32,044 --> 00:28:33,671
What's the matter, fella?

308
00:28:33,921 --> 00:28:35,548
Somebody stole my horse.

309
00:28:35,756 --> 00:28:38,054
I told you to get
out of town by sunset.

310
00:28:38,258 --> 00:28:41,102
You missing a bay mare
that was tied to the hitching rail?

311
00:28:41,261 --> 00:28:43,684
Saw a feller come and take her
just a spell ago.

312
00:28:43,889 --> 00:28:45,562
Well, what did he look like?

313
00:28:45,766 --> 00:28:48,235
Well, he was about
this tall, and he had this...

314
00:28:48,393 --> 00:28:49,861
Get him, Frank!

315
00:29:13,460 --> 00:29:18,261
Let's put him inside here and get to
the bank and make that withdrawal.

316
00:29:23,095 --> 00:29:25,814
All right, boys. The fun's over.

317
00:29:26,348 --> 00:29:29,272
Throw out your guns
and step out with your hands up.

318
00:29:29,476 --> 00:29:32,901
You'd better listen, marshal.
I've got three sticks of dynamite here.

319
00:29:33,063 --> 00:29:34,155
Don't be a fool.

320
00:29:51,123 --> 00:29:53,626
The outlaw life
seemed a shortcut to easy money...

321
00:29:53,834 --> 00:29:57,464
which could buy liquor, women,
and a turn at the gambling table...

322
00:29:57,629 --> 00:29:59,802
but there were honest
men with dreams...

323
00:29:59,965 --> 00:30:02,593
who would fight to protect their...
- Let's get that beer.

324
00:30:02,759 --> 00:30:06,855
and who were to plant
the roots that would grow into a nation.

325
00:30:13,145 --> 00:30:15,068
Blue Ridge won't buy it.

326
00:30:17,316 --> 00:30:20,786
I don't build a thing that's gonna
be a slum in 20 years...

327
00:30:21,361 --> 00:30:23,204
and I won't doze those hills.

328
00:30:23,363 --> 00:30:26,037
What I build conforms to the land.

329
00:30:26,533 --> 00:30:29,286
And you can't hear the
toilets flush next door.

330
00:30:30,454 --> 00:30:33,298
You want our help,
you'll have to let me work on it.

331
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:37,503
Well, up to a point,
I want your help.

332
00:30:37,711 --> 00:30:40,089
Up to a point, I'll give it.

333
00:31:31,681 --> 00:31:33,729
When do I get a look-see?

334
00:31:34,810 --> 00:31:36,778
In a couple days.

335
00:31:37,229 --> 00:31:39,948
Guard says you were here
till after midnight last night.

336
00:31:40,107 --> 00:31:41,609
Yeah. That's the way I work.

337
00:31:42,359 --> 00:31:44,157
Somebody once said...

338
00:31:44,361 --> 00:31:46,739
I forget who.
...that he never looked back...

339
00:31:46,905 --> 00:31:49,203
because something might
be gaining on him.

340
00:31:50,200 --> 00:31:51,873
What's gaining on you, Paul?

341
00:31:53,703 --> 00:31:55,922
Twenty million dollar investment.
What else?

342
00:31:56,623 --> 00:32:00,753
Well, I was gonna ask you to have
dinner with me at the club...

343
00:32:00,919 --> 00:32:02,842
but I don't think
you'd be very good company.

344
00:32:03,004 --> 00:32:04,221
No, I don't think I would.

345
00:32:04,423 --> 00:32:06,748
It might amuse you, though.
Being from New York,

346
00:32:06,774 --> 00:32:08,624
maybe you never seen
a club like this.

347
00:32:08,760 --> 00:32:11,980
It's a gun club.
We shoot guns.

348
00:32:16,393 --> 00:32:20,068
So goddamn much hoopla
from the gun control people.

349
00:32:20,313 --> 00:32:22,407
Half the nation's scared
to even hold a gun!

350
00:32:22,566 --> 00:32:25,285
You know, like it was a snake,
it was gonna bite you or something.

351
00:32:25,444 --> 00:32:27,572
Hell, a gun is just a tool...

352
00:32:28,572 --> 00:32:31,121
like a hammer or an ax.

353
00:32:31,533 --> 00:32:34,127
Wasn't long ago,
used to put food on the table...

354
00:32:34,327 --> 00:32:38,252
keep foxes out of the chicken coop,
rustlers off the range...

355
00:32:38,457 --> 00:32:39,674
bandits out of the bank.

356
00:32:39,833 --> 00:32:42,052
Paul, how long since
you held a pistol in your hand?

357
00:32:43,336 --> 00:32:46,681
- A long time.
- Hm.

358
00:32:47,340 --> 00:32:50,264
- Which war was yours, Korea?
- Yeah.

359
00:32:50,594 --> 00:32:52,847
- See much action?
- A little.

360
00:32:53,096 --> 00:32:54,518
Were you infantry?

361
00:32:56,266 --> 00:32:59,019
- I was a CO in a medical unit.
- Oh.

362
00:32:59,186 --> 00:33:01,314
Commanding officer, huh?

363
00:33:01,980 --> 00:33:04,449
Conscientious objector.

364
00:33:05,275 --> 00:33:06,743
Oh, Christ.

365
00:33:06,943 --> 00:33:10,664
What a guest to bring
to a gun club. Heh.

366
00:33:10,822 --> 00:33:12,790
You're probably one
of them knee-jerk liberals...

367
00:33:12,949 --> 00:33:17,375
thinks us gun boys shoot our guns
because it's an extension of our penises.

368
00:33:17,913 --> 00:33:19,836
I never thought about
it that way...

369
00:33:20,165 --> 00:33:21,508
but it could be true.

370
00:33:22,083 --> 00:33:23,835
Well, maybe it is...

371
00:33:24,294 --> 00:33:26,262
but this is gun country.

372
00:33:26,421 --> 00:33:28,594
Can't even own a handgun
in New York City.

373
00:33:28,757 --> 00:33:31,055
Out here, I hardly know a man
that doesn't own one.

374
00:33:31,426 --> 00:33:33,053
And I'll tell you something...

375
00:33:33,220 --> 00:33:35,564
unlike your city,
we can walk our streets...

376
00:33:35,722 --> 00:33:37,895
and through our parks
at night and feel safe.

377
00:33:38,183 --> 00:33:42,529
Muggers operating out here, they'd
just plain get their asses blown off.

378
00:33:42,854 --> 00:33:45,573
Here. Slip these on.

379
00:33:46,024 --> 00:33:48,903
All righty.
This is a percussion pistol.

380
00:33:49,110 --> 00:33:50,612
1842.

381
00:33:54,533 --> 00:33:56,831
You ever handled one
of those before?

382
00:33:58,453 --> 00:34:00,000
You know how to fire it?

383
00:34:00,705 --> 00:34:02,082
Watch the kick.

384
00:34:02,290 --> 00:34:05,134
Boy, you're gonna think that
your arm's gonna hit the ceiling.

385
00:34:15,387 --> 00:34:16,934
Goddamn!

386
00:34:17,138 --> 00:34:18,936
Paul, you hit dead center!

387
00:34:19,391 --> 00:34:21,234
Mind if I try this Hogleg Colt?

388
00:34:21,393 --> 00:34:22,770
No.

389
00:34:22,936 --> 00:34:26,031
Well, you a peculiar
conscientious objector.

390
00:34:26,523 --> 00:34:28,446
- These notches for real?
- Yeah.

391
00:34:28,608 --> 00:34:31,987
Belonged to a gunfighter
named Candy Dan, 1890.

392
00:34:32,153 --> 00:34:35,123
Hm. I do know something
about guns, Aimes.

393
00:34:35,282 --> 00:34:38,035
I grew up with them.
All kinds of guns.

394
00:34:38,994 --> 00:34:40,917
You see, my father was a hunter.

395
00:34:41,162 --> 00:34:43,881
I guess out here you'd
call him a gunman.

396
00:34:44,165 --> 00:34:46,759
My mother was the
other side of the coin.

397
00:34:48,086 --> 00:34:51,056
When my father was killed
in a hunting accident...

398
00:34:52,132 --> 00:34:54,430
Some fool mistook him
for a deer, you see.

399
00:34:55,093 --> 00:34:56,936
My mother won the toss.

400
00:34:57,220 --> 00:34:59,348
I never touched a gun since.

401
00:35:01,141 --> 00:35:03,109
I loved my father.

402
00:35:15,030 --> 00:35:16,907
There are your hills.

403
00:35:17,949 --> 00:35:20,372
Every house has a part
of one for a backyard...

404
00:35:20,535 --> 00:35:22,128
for kids, dogs, horses.

405
00:35:22,704 --> 00:35:25,799
Four hundred houses,
100 more than you allowed for...

406
00:35:25,999 --> 00:35:28,047
and you still have 12 hills.

407
00:35:30,378 --> 00:35:32,597
I'm catching the 10:40
back to New York.

408
00:35:33,214 --> 00:35:34,887
What do I tell them?

409
00:35:36,176 --> 00:35:37,974
You tell them I'll buy
it if they will.

410
00:35:58,239 --> 00:35:59,991
You're checking this bag
through, aren't you?

411
00:36:00,408 --> 00:36:01,785
- Yeah.
- Good.

412
00:36:01,993 --> 00:36:04,872
Let me slip a little going-away
present in there for you.

413
00:36:06,790 --> 00:36:07,916
Thank you.

414
00:36:13,171 --> 00:36:15,674
<i>Trans World Airlines Flight 63...</i>

415
00:36:15,840 --> 00:36:17,736
<i>- ...from Tucson to New
York is now boarding...</i>

416
00:36:17,762 --> 00:36:19,335
Good morning, sir.
How are you today?

417
00:36:19,719 --> 00:36:21,062
Checking one bag?

418
00:36:21,262 --> 00:36:24,812
Paul, I can't thank you enough
for what you did for me.

419
00:36:25,016 --> 00:36:29,817
I want you to know if you ever
get tired of living in that toilet...

420
00:36:30,563 --> 00:36:32,190
you're welcome here.

421
00:36:34,651 --> 00:36:36,904
<i>Trans World airlines Flight 7...</i>

422
00:36:37,070 --> 00:36:39,619
<i>to London and Frankfurt
is now boarding.</i>

423
00:36:39,781 --> 00:36:42,284
<i>Passengers should
proceed to Gate 11</i>

424
00:36:42,450 --> 00:36:44,168
- Welcome home, Dad.
- Hi, Jack.

425
00:36:44,327 --> 00:36:46,455
I halfway expected to see Carol.

426
00:36:46,871 --> 00:36:48,965
Come on.
Let's go get your bags.

427
00:36:50,417 --> 00:36:51,714
What is it?

428
00:36:53,169 --> 00:36:55,263
She's in the hospital.

429
00:36:57,757 --> 00:36:59,430
When I last spoke to you on the phone...

430
00:36:59,592 --> 00:37:02,391
you said she was feeling better
after coming back from the shore.

431
00:37:04,222 --> 00:37:07,226
Well, I didn't see any need to get you
all disturbed on a long-distance call.

432
00:37:07,392 --> 00:37:11,568
<i>Will Mr. Cory, a passenger on
Trans World Airlines Flight 100...</i>

433
00:37:11,730 --> 00:37:13,858
<i>from Vancouver,
please report to...</i>

434
00:37:14,023 --> 00:37:15,900
Oh, come on, Dad,
don't do a number...

435
00:37:16,401 --> 00:37:18,028
Don't do a number on me.

436
00:37:18,403 --> 00:37:20,872
Look, there was
nothing you could do.

437
00:37:21,656 --> 00:37:24,876
They haven't even let me see her
for two days.

438
00:37:27,328 --> 00:37:29,956
They tried insulin
shock yesterday.

439
00:37:30,248 --> 00:37:32,467
She's not responding.

440
00:37:33,501 --> 00:37:36,425
You want the technical jargon?
I can reel off yards of it:

441
00:37:36,755 --> 00:37:41,761
Catatonia, dementia praecox,
passive schizoid paranoia.

442
00:37:43,178 --> 00:37:47,149
It all boils down to the fact that she's
had an experience that she can't face...

443
00:37:47,307 --> 00:37:49,856
and she's running away from it
inside herself.

444
00:37:50,018 --> 00:37:53,443
<i>Will Mrs. Lager, a passenger
on Trans World Airlines...</i>

445
00:37:53,605 --> 00:37:55,027
<i>Flight 45 to Paris...</i>

446
00:37:55,231 --> 00:37:57,825
<i>please contact the
information desk...</i>

447
00:37:57,984 --> 00:37:59,861
You didn't handle her right, Jack.

448
00:38:00,862 --> 00:38:02,956
Aw, Christ, Dad.

449
00:38:04,199 --> 00:38:06,201
I'll get other doctors.

450
00:38:06,701 --> 00:38:10,797
- Who are these goddamn doctors you have?
- They're good doctors.

451
00:38:14,125 --> 00:38:16,594
Dad,
she's almost a goddamn vegetable.

452
00:38:49,285 --> 00:38:52,289
If you don't sign the papers,
what happens?

453
00:38:53,998 --> 00:38:57,377
I guess they keep her in the hospital
until the insurance runs out.

454
00:38:57,544 --> 00:38:58,841
That won't be too long.

455
00:38:59,003 --> 00:39:02,724
If you sign the papers and
she's committed, what then?

456
00:39:04,050 --> 00:39:07,850
Well, I've got an insurance policy
that covers it up to about 600 a month.

457
00:39:08,263 --> 00:39:11,312
They've recommended
a sanatorium out in Long Island.

458
00:39:12,308 --> 00:39:14,026
Jack...

459
00:39:15,520 --> 00:39:18,319
This commitment,
is it a one-way thing?

460
00:39:19,691 --> 00:39:22,285
Nobody can answer that, Dad.

461
00:39:23,695 --> 00:39:25,538
You wanna know what they are?

462
00:39:25,697 --> 00:39:28,200
<i>They're statistics
on a police blotter.</i>

463
00:39:28,741 --> 00:39:31,870
Mom and Carol, along with
thousands of other people.

464
00:39:32,453 --> 00:39:35,252
And there is nothing
that we can do to stop it.

465
00:39:36,040 --> 00:39:37,792
Nothing but cut and run.

466
00:42:06,274 --> 00:42:10,745
Oh, what a bummer, man. That was
the worst fucking movie I've ever seen.

467
00:43:41,786 --> 00:43:43,254
You got money, man?

468
00:43:47,792 --> 00:43:49,135
Shit, I'll kill you!

469
00:43:49,335 --> 00:43:51,212
Give me your money
or I'll bust you up!

470
00:44:35,131 --> 00:44:36,804
Oh, Jesus.

471
00:44:37,049 --> 00:44:38,471
Oh, Jesus.

472
00:44:38,676 --> 00:44:40,394
Jesus Christ.

473
00:44:40,595 --> 00:44:43,474
Ohh. Oh, Jesus.

474
00:45:19,759 --> 00:45:21,727
Good morning, inspector.

475
00:45:22,887 --> 00:45:25,015
Good morning.
What do we got?

476
00:45:25,181 --> 00:45:27,775
We got a corpse down here,
one bullet hole in his chest.

477
00:45:28,017 --> 00:45:30,662
